Introduction

This is a report on the analysis of the raw nucleotide data from a ChIP-Seq experiment performed by the Irish Cancer Society on BreastPredict project. The data focuses on the 21st Chromosome from the Human Genome (Feb. 2009 (GRCh37/hg19) release). The document covers the interrogation of potential regulatory role of a specific transcription factor in a human breast cancer cell line through a full ChIP-seq analysis and includes genome-wide binding location of the same TF along with the expected binding motif which shows a probable TF-DNA interaction and gene regulation.

Software Used

  • fastqc
    • Fast quality check on fastq data
  • bowtie2
    • A fast and sensitive gapped read aligner
  • samtools
    • Samtools is a suite of programs for interacting with high-throughput sequencing data
  • macs2
    • Model-based Analysis of ChIP-Seq
  • bedtools
    • Swiss-army knife of tools for a wide-range of genomics analysis tasks.
  • IGV
    • A high-performance visualization tool for interactive exploration of large, integrated genomic datasets.
  • bash
    • Standard Linux shell
  • GREAT
    • GREAT predicts functions of cis-regulatory regions.
  • meme-suite
    • MEME Suite allows the biologist to discover novel motifs in collections of unaligned nucleotide or protein sequences, and to perform a wide variety of other motif-based analyses.
  • rsat
    • Pipeline for discovering motifs in massive ChIP-seq peak sequences.
  • pavis
    • Annotation and visualization of ChIP-seq data

Preprocessing

Data

  • chr21.fa - The reference genome used for the analysis
  • chip.fastq - The experiment file with reads of dna that have immunoprecipitated. This forms the case.
    • ChIP-Seq is used to analyse protein interactions with DNA. ChIP-seq combines chromatin immunoprecipitation with massively parallel DNA sequencing to identify the binding sites of DNA-associated proteins.
  • input.fastq - The control

Reference Genome Indexing

The reference genome has to be indexed in order to align the reads properly. The indexing is done with bowtie. Bowtie2 is an ultrafast and memory-efficient tool for aligning sequencing reads to long reference sequences. It is particularly good at aligning reads of about 50 up to 100s or 1,000s of characters, and particularly good at aligning to relatively long (e.g. mammalian) genomes. Hence it was chosen.

module load bowtie
##bowtie splits the files into chunks(with .bt2 extension). hg19 is the prefix to each file
bowtie2-build chr21.fa hg19

File Operations

The aligned sequences are post-processed to compress them into binary files, remove duplicates, sort and index them. Samtools is used for the post-processing

module load samtools
time samtools view -Sb input.sam > input.bam  ##Compresses sam files to bam(binary) files
time samtools view -Sb chip.sam > chip.bam
samtools rmdup input.bam input.nodup.bam  ##Remove duplicates from the binary sequence files
samtools rmdup chip.bam chip.nodup.bam
time samtools sort chip.nodup.bam chip.nodup.sorted.bam   ##Sort the sequences based on their leftmost coordinates
time samtools sort input.nodup.bam input.nodup.sorted.bam
time samtools index chip.nodup.sorted.bam  ##Index the binary files
time samtools index input.nodup.sorted.bam
time samtools flagstat chip.nodup.sorted.bam > chip.flagstat.txt  ##Get the statistics of the alignment files
time samtools flagstat input.nodup.sorted.bam > input.flagstat.txt
diff -y chip.flagstat.txt input.flagstat.txt ##Display the difference between the statistics

Data Analysis

Putative regions where transcription factors binds to the chromosome are isolated through peak calling. Peak calling is a computational method used to identify areas in a genome that have been enriched with aligned reads as a consequence of performing a ChIP-sequencing experiment. Peaks correspond to areas which are “overexpressed”. MACS2 is used to call peaks.

time macs2 callpeak -t chip.nodup.sorted.bam -c input.nodup.sorted.bam -f BAM -g hs -n macs_out --call-summits -B

Based on the above reports from GREAT, it is evident that the pathways involved in the regulatory expression of the TF lies in the FOXA1 and the estrogen receptor network. As this paper suggests, FOXA1 is a key determinant of estrogen receptor function and endocrine response. Thus we can assume from the above reports that the TF in question is related to the estrogen receptors.

Motif Discovery

Motif analysis and discovery was performed multiple times using different known motif databases to check for convergence

A sequence motif is a nucleotide or amino-acid sequence pattern that is widespread and has, or is conjectured to have, a biological significance. Motifs span several nucleotides of varied lengths and are highly probable TFs binding sites. The seq_nodup_output1.fasta file is used for comprehensive motif analysis & discovery.

MEME-ChIP

MEME-ChIP is used for motif analysis and discovery. Since MEME is used for smaller datasets, MEME-ChIP is the better option for larger datasets. MEME-ChIP is a pipeline which:

  • Isolates the most frequently occurring sequence length (fasta-most)
  • Outputs the length portion of the sequence centred on the original sequence (fasta-center)
  • Shuffle each sequence in a file of fasta sequences without shuffling the order of the sequences (fasta-shuffle-letter)
  • Estimate a Markov model from the shuffled sequences (fasta-get-markov)
  • Motif discovery (meme)
  • Find discriminative regular expressions (dreme)
  • Local motif enrichment analysis (centrimo)
  • Search for existing motifs from a database (tomtom)
  • Looks for significant spacings between a primary motif and each motif in a library of secondary motifs (spamo)
  • Scan a set of sequences for motifs (fimo)

(It automatically calculates the background score)

MEME-ChIP Submission Form:(Up)

The seq_nodup_output1.fasta file is used as the primary sequence list. The motif analysis is performed and the resulting motifs found are cros-checked from a database of known motifs.

MEME-Options:(Up)

The options chosen for the MEME analysis are:

  • The distribution of the motifs are assumed to be ‘Zero or one occurence per sequence’. It is more lenient and a balanced assumption when the distribution itself is only partially known or obfuscated.
  • The expected count of motifs that MEME should find before it confirms any significance is 5. It also acts as defult upper limit to stop running the algorithm.
  • Width of the motifs are assumed to be between 6 and 30. Since we need to estimate the binding sites of the TF, a larger width is chosen.
  • An overall E-value of 0.05 is chosen. Any motif below this threshold is discarded as non-significant.

The above parameters gave several motifs, out of which two with the good matches are chosen.

Results

The above analysis produced results which were same in terms of the sequence of the motifs were the same, but when cross-checked with the different known motifs databases, they produced different results. The similar motifs for the results, excluding the first significant motif, did not converge.

The converging results are:

The similar motifs found point towards ESR1 and ESR2. The E-values, p-values and q-values, though different, are proximal.

Footnotes on ESRX

  • ESR1: (Estrogen receptor)
    • Nuclear hormone receptor. The steroid hormones and their receptors are involved in the regulation of eukaryotic gene expression and affect cellular proliferation and differentiation in target tissues. Can activate the transcriptional activity of TFF1(Breast Cancer Estrogen-Inducible Protein)
  • ESR2: (Estrogen receptor beta)
    • Nuclear hormone receptor. Binds estrogens with an affinity similar to that of ESR1, and activates expression of reporter genes containing estrogen response elements (ERE) in an estrogen-dependent manner.

RSAT

RSAT provides a set of tools to analyse cis-regulatory elements in genome sequences. This part of the analysis was performed to check if the results differed when using different motif discovery tools.

Most of the motifs analyzed are different from the results obtained from MEME-ChIP. But it points to some interesting Candidates like FOXP1 which acts as a repressor gene, ERRq(ESRRA) which acts like an estrogen receptor.

Analysis

Factorbook breifly explain that estrogen receptors are involved in pathological processes including breast cancer, endometrial cancer, and osteoporosis. Alternative promoter usage and alternative splicing result in dozens of transcript variants, but the full-length nature of many of these variants has not been determined. On browsing the genes associated with ESR1, UCSC Genes shows that the following genes are in direct association and reside in the 21st chromosome(which is the current chromosome under observation)

  • NRIP1
  • PRMT2

Viewing these genes on the UCSC Genome Browser uncovered that at chr21:46,902,033-46,902,170, ESR1 was directly in line with the Peak Track.

Estrogen Binding

A similar entry was found in the positions of motifs found by MEME. It had the sequence AGGTCAGGGTGACCT and was located in chr21:46901839-46902327. This looks like a potential binding by a TF at the span of the region, owing to it prefixing a TSS.

IGV shows a peak at the region spanning the motif location

Conclusion

Thus this report is concluded with a good confidence level that this is the expected binding motif of ESR1 transcription factor.
